 archives, including long-suppressed state and Communist Party documents, to uncover the secrets of the Gulag and how it became a central component of Soviet ideology and social policy.Khlevniuk argues persuasively that the Stalinist penal camps created in the 1930s were essentially different from previous camps. He shows that political motivations and paranoia about potential enemies contributed no more to the expansion of the Gulag than the economic incentive of slave labor did. And he offers powerful evidence that the Great Terror was planned centrally and targeted against particular categories of the population. Khlevniuk makes a signal contribution to Soviet history with this exceptionally informed and balanced view of the Gulag.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aConcentration campszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aForced laborzSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aPolitical prisonerszSoviet Union. 0aPrisonszSoviet UnionxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aHabeck, Mary, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRadosh, Ronald, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSevostianov, Grigory, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package Archivez978311053801440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300160642423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300160642.jpg  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook Package Archive  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles